+methodology-page('ISA 240', 'A summary of what ISA 240 has to say about sampling journals during a statutory/external audit', 'isa')
	h1 What does the ISA say?
	p.content ISA 240 requires the auditor to "Test the appropriateness of journal entries recorded in the general ledger"
		+footnote-link(1)
		|. It states that "the auditorâ€™s assessment of the risks of material misstatement due to fraud may assist the auditor to identify specific classes of journal entries and other adjustments for testing", and suggests the following as examples of the characteristics of fraudulent journals:
		ul.content
			li made to unrelated, unusual, or seldom-used accounts,
			li made by individuals who typically do not make journal entries,
			li recorded at the end of the period or as post-closing entries that have little or no explanation or description,
			li made either before or during the preparation of the financial statements that do not have account numbers,
			li containing round numbers or consistent ending numbers
	p.content Of course, this is a wide variety of sampling methods for an auditor to choose from. Most auditors therefore choose to keep things simple: to choose a sample of journals posted outside of normal working hours and round number amounts. However, the regulator would rather that auditors used more varied sampling methods, as they 
		a(href="methodology-recommendations") stated earlier this year
